{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti 7.58** is the specific verse in Chapter 7 that refers to the king's *ṣaḍguṇya* (six expedients or measures of foreign policy). It states:\n\n> But with a Brahmana who is distinguished among them all, a wise man, the king should deliberate on the supreme counsel connected with the **six political expedients**. // Mn_7.58 //[^1]\n\nThis is the key reference in the chapter to the *ṣaḍguṇya*, a concept drawn from ancient Indian political theory (also elaborated in Kauṭilya's *Arthaśāstra*). Manu does not list the six expedients explicitly here—*sandhi* (peace), *vigraha* (war), *āsana* (halting/stationing), *yāna* (marching), *dvēṣaṇa* (sowing discord), and *upēya* (alliance/seeking aid)—but instructs the king to deliberate on them with a trusted Brahmin advisor.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 7, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-c8856b).\n\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 7 (full context read from translation), via the preceding verses on royal counsel (e.g., Mn_7.56–59) and envoys skilled in policy (Mn_7.63–68). No explicit list of the six appears in this chapter.",
